<div class="thumb tright">
<div class="thumbinner" style="width:182px;"><a href="/wiki/File:WI-FI_Range_Diagram.png" class="image" title="A diagram showing a Wi-Fi network"><img alt="" src="http://upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/f/fe/WI-FI_Range_Diagram.png/180px-WI-FI_Range_Diagram.png" width="180" height="135" border="0" class="thumbimage" /></a>
<div class="thumbcaption">
<div class="magnify"><a href="/wiki/File:WI-FI_Range_Diagram.png" class="internal" title="Enlarge"><img src="/skins-1.5/common/images/magnify-clip.png" width="15" height="11" alt="" /></a></div>
A diagram showing a Wi-Fi network</div>
</div>
</div>
<p>A <b>Hot-spot</b>, or <b>Hot spot</b> or <b>HotSpot</b> is a venue that offers <a href="/wiki/Internet_access" title="Internet access">internet access</a> over a <a href="/wiki/Wireless_LAN" title="Wireless LAN">wireless LAN</a>. It should not be confused with a <a href="/wiki/Hot-zone" title="Hot-zone">Hot-zone</a>, which is an internet-sharing <a href="/wiki/WWAN" title="WWAN" class="mw-redirect">wireless wide area network</a>.</p>
